Descriptive Statistics: Summarizes, organizes, and visualizes data using techniques like mean, median, mode, variance, and graphs (histograms, bar plots).

Inferential Statistics: Uses sample data to make generalizations, predictions, or inferences about a larger population, including hypothesis testing and regression analysis.

Descriptive Statistics Types
These methods are used to describe, organize, and summarize data into manageable forms. 
Measures of Central Tendency: Identify the "center" or typical value of a dataset.
Mean: The mathematical average.
Median: The middle value in a sorted list.
Mode: The most frequently occurring value.
Measures of Dispersion (Variability): Describe how spread out the data points are.
Range: Difference between the highest and lowest values.
Variance: Average of the squared differences from the Mean.
Standard Deviation: The average distance of each data point from the mean.
Interquartile Range (IQR): The spread of the middle 50% of the data.
Measures of Frequency Distribution: Show how often each value occurs in a dataset.
Frequency Tables: Listing data points and their counts.
Relative Frequency: Percentages or proportions of the total.
Measures of Position: Describe where a specific value falls in relation to others.
Percentiles: The value below which a percentage of data falls.
Quartiles: Values that divide the data into four equal parts.
Graphical Representations: Visual tools to present data patterns.
Histograms, Bar Charts, Pie Charts, and Box Plots. 



Inferential Statistics Types
These methods allow researchers to test hypotheses and generalize findings from a sample to an entire population. 
