Hypothesis Testing: Determines if there is enough evidence in a sample to support a specific claim about the population.
T-tests: Compare the means of two groups.
Z-tests: Compare means when the population variance is known and the sample size is large.
ANOVA (Analysis of Variance): Compares means across three or more groups.
Chi-Square Tests: Used for categorical data to check for independence.
Regression Analysis: Examines the relationship between a dependent variable and one or more independent variables to make predictions.
Simple Linear Regression: One independent variable.
Multiple Regression: Two or more independent variables.
Logistic Regression: Used when the outcome is binary (e.g., Yes/No).
Estimation (Point and Interval): Estimates population parameters based on sample data.
Confidence Intervals: A range of values likely to contain the true population parameter with a certain level of confidence.
Correlation Analysis: Measures the strength and direction of the relationship between two variables.
Pearson Correlation: For linear relationships between continuous variables
